<task id="AUTHV2-013" project="Spaarke Auth v2 + Hardening">
  <metadata>
    <title>Implement useAuth() React hook — function-based public API</title>
    <phase>A — Core library rebuild</phase>
    <tags>auth, library, react, hook, FULL</tags>
    <status>not-started</status>
    <estimated-effort>2 hours</estimated-effort>
    <dependencies>011, 012</dependencies>
    <parallel-safe>false</parallel-safe>
  </metadata>
  <prompt>
    Add the React hook useAuth() that becomes the primary public API for consumers. Returns { isAuthenticated, getAccessToken, authenticatedFetch, tenantId, logout }. NO token: string value anywhere. authenticatedFetch is bound to the singleton provider; getAccessToken is the narrow escape for SSE cases.

    Hook implementation should be simple: read from the singleton getAuthProvider(). The provider's getAccessToken always goes through the in-memory cache + JWT exp validation, so callers automatically get refreshed tokens.
  </prompt>
  <role>Senior React + TypeScript engineer. Hook design is the most-used API surface; ergonomics matter.</role>
  <goal>
    @spaarke/auth exports a useAuth() hook. Function-based return shape: no token value. All ~30 consumers in Phase B will use this hook.
  </goal>
  <knowledge>
    <files>
      <file>.claude/AUDIT-FINDINGS-AUTH-SYSTEM.md §4.1 (function-based contract principle)</file>
      <file>.claude/AUDIT-FINDINGS-AUTH-SYSTEM.md §4.2 (target public APIs)</file>
      <file>src/client/shared/Spaarke.Auth/src/authenticatedFetch.ts (existing — wrap for the hook)</file>
      <file>src/client/shared/Spaarke.Auth/src/initAuth.ts (singleton provider)</file>
    </files>
  </knowledge>
  <steps>
    <step>Create src/client/shared/Spaarke.Auth/src/useAuth.ts: import { getAuthProvider } from './initAuth'; export function useAuth() that returns object with isAuthenticated (sync getter from provider), getAccessToken (async, delegates to provider), authenticatedFetch (the existing exported function, NOT bound — the existing impl already uses getAuthProvider internally), tenantId (sync getter from provider.getCachedTenantId()), logout (stub for now, implemented in task 014).</step>
    <step>Decision on hook reactivity: useAuth does NOT use useState for token (that would be the snapshot bug we're eliminating). isAuthenticated CAN be reactive via useState + an event listener for auth state changes (set up in 015). For now, isAuthenticated returns provider.isAuthenticated() synchronously — consumers re-check on each call.</step>
    <step>Update src/index.ts: export useAuth, AuthenticatedFetchFn type. Remove any export that returns a token string (verify with grep).</step>
    <step>Verify no exported function or interface has `accessToken: string` or `token: string` in its type. Use grep over src/ exports.</step>
    <step>Add an ESLint rule to package.json or eslint config: ban /Authorization:\s*['"`]Bearer\s+\$\{/ regex in any file other than src/authenticatedFetch.ts.</step>
    <step>Write unit test for useAuth that mounts a component, calls useAuth, and verifies the returned object shape.</step>
    <step>Run tsc --noEmit. Run tests.</step>
  </steps>
  <acceptance-criteria>
    <criterion>useAuth() exported from @spaarke/auth.</criterion>
    <criterion>Return type has NO field that is `token: string` or `accessToken: string`.</criterion>
    <criterion>Provides getAccessToken (async), authenticatedFetch (function), isAuthenticated (bool), tenantId (string), logout (function).</criterion>
    <criterion>ESLint rule active: bans Authorization Bearer template literals outside authenticatedFetch.ts.</criterion>
    <criterion>Unit test for useAuth passes.</criterion>
  </acceptance-criteria>
</task>
